snippet.textDisplay: As an actual sufferer of EDS, I can say with certainty that this woman is SO full of bull. Before physical therapy, my hips especially would dislocate frequently, my spine curved severely and I still kept a job at a call center. Now that I  able to manage my symptoms and use compression ware, I am ab esthetician and am able to do light exercises to keep healthy. The pain is still an issue at times, but depending on the classification or subtype of EDS, it is easily conceivable to live a fairly normal life. If this woman was as bad as she says she is with EDS, she would be in a wheelchair and more than likely in a special care home. People will do anything to just get out of life, when the ones who are sick will actually put forth the effort to live life

snippet.textDisplay: Oookay. So from personal experience, I know that EDS often does go undiagnosed for many years. Most medical professionals either don’t have a clue what it is or are misinformed. I cannot stress this enough: Disease. Begins. Before. Diagnosis. Many chronically ill patients suffer for years, even decades before doctors decide to take their pain seriously, let alone figure out what is wrong with them. Some people NEVER get a diagnosis. Does that mean they’re not suffering? Absolutely not. In fact, living with an undiagnosed disease is much more debilitating, because you are not receiving treatments, AND because most people hold the opinions that our friend here Dr. Phil does. They think that if they can’t immediately see a disability, it doesn’t exist. That’s just not how it works. So many people who are already in so much pain physically are now experiencing emotional pain because people don’t sympathize, but attack them for “faking.” Sure, there are people out there that have mental health issues and fake an illness. But that is not the majority, and it is NEVER okay to assume something like that without ample evidence. Really, it hurts.

I do understand the skeptic attitude about EDS, but as a EDS hypermobility patient, it is extremely difficult to get an official diagnosis. This woman is helpless. She needs real doctors that won't just feed her pills she doesn't necessarily need.

snippet.textDisplay: I have been diagnosed with EDS and I suffer acute pain everyday, if it wasn’t for large doses of morphine I really don’t know what I’d do. After finding life too much I asked adult social services for help and now have a carer. I’m in the uk, I don’t know how it works in the states, but I asked for external help as my eldest child was helping me too much personally and helping me look after my three young children which was unfair. Now my carer helps me personally and supports me to care for me younger children freeing my older child to lead her own life. EDS is so very painful, I can sleep for days on end, having a bath will wipe me out completely as it drains all my energy. Don’t underestimate what this poor lady goes through. If I didn’t have children that needed me there are times with the pain I would have killed myself. She doesn’t say it to guilt her daughter, but because life is just too much. She can’t look after herself, I know as I’m there too.

snippet.textDisplay: As someone who has EDS I fear this is going to give us a bad reputation... it’s painful and frustrating but I still go to school, work and swimming has proven to be the best way for me to get moving! My hips pop out of place and pop right back in, my knees ache but I take some ibuprofen and go along with my day. It took me years to get a formal diagnosis. I was around 7 years old when that happened. I remember all the tests that were done to confirm EDS, and the doctor that diagnosed me has since passed but knowing that it’s real and not in my head is such a relief. I have paper work through the university that I’m at stating I have this disease so I’m physically limited but that’s okay I know those limits. I’m almost 20 years old and happy.

snippet.textDisplay: I feel bad for people with actual EDS. This is seemingly the latest 'fad' illness for people with Munchausens these days. So many liars and scammers. As someone with chronic illnesses these people disgust me.

snippet.textDisplay: Would love to see the rest of it! 🤭  I have eds - you don't get it after a divorce, it's a life long genetic issue, she can flex her fingers but not everyone who is hypermobile has EDS. When she is saying she is in pain it sounds so hollow, I'm wheelchair bound with EDS and a rare neurological condition and work two jobs, I find the more I sit and do nothing and say I can't do something I'm a lot worse and depression makes my ability to manage worse so keeping busy, a good physiotherapist makes a huge difference, if it started after her divorce I'd be inclined to say fibromyalgia as trauma can trigger this.

snippet.textDisplay:
People get a mental diagnosis and after that they find out about eds.
If people are tired they get grumpy.
If people are in pain they get grumpy.
What if you feel that every day and people say it's in your head.
Yes you go crazy.
Until you find out it's not in your head but it is in your body.
If the fatigue and pain is managed the mental bit is taken care at the same time.

snippet.textDisplay: I have 2 parents with chronic health issues.  One is post CVA with physical limitations and needs personal care and assistance.  The other with heart failure, severe COPD.  Neither one drives and both lack extensive physical activity.  I clean. I take care of property.  Laundry 🧺 clean clothes. Grocery shopping.. Medication pick ups. I do what I can.   We manage for now.  I have a background providing care to elders.  We need to care for our parents.  Which isn’t always a piece of cake 🍰   I pray for them.   I pray that we all can try to assist.   I’m a caretaker and I need strength to provide and not be critical.  Good days and not so good days.  Your wisdom and insight along with remedial recommendations and/or suggestions.  would be greatly appreciated.
